## What happened

In **.NET 11**, Apple's cryptography libraries dropped DSA support, so .NET removed DSA from macOS. Calling `DSA.Create()` now **throws at runtime** on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you're **verifying legacy DSA signatures** (not generating new ones), you have two options:

### Option 1 — Platform guard (keep DSA on Windows/Linux)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 — Migrate to ECDSA (recommended long-term)

Re-sign your artifacts with a modern algorithm and verify with:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
ecdsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**If you must verify existing DSA signatures on macOS**, you'll need a third-party library (e.g., Bouncy Castle) that provides a software DSA implementation independent of the OS.
